"""Enriched diagnostic intelligence for the most common codes (from Dipstick).
Each entry: definition, system, severity, common_causes, diagnostic_steps,
follow_up_questions, and real-world shop notes.
"""

ENRICHED_CODES = {'P0171': {'code': 'P0171', 'definition': 'System Too Lean (Bank 1)', 'system': 'Fuel/Air Metering', 'severity': 'moderate', 'common_causes': ['Vacuum leak (intake gasket, PCV hose, cracked intake boot)', 'Dirty or failing MAF sensor', 'Weak fuel pump or restricted fuel filter', 'Faulty fuel pressure regulator', 'Exhaust leak before front O2 sensor', 'Failing O2 sensor (less common as primary cause)'], 'diagnostic_steps': ['Check fuel trims with scanner (LTFT > +10% confirms lean condition)', 'Smoke test the intake for vacuum leaks', 'Inspect and clean MAF sensor with proper MAF cleaner', 'Check fuel pressure at the rail vs. spec, key on / engine running', 'Inspect PCV system and intake boots for cracks'], 'follow_up_questions': ['P0174 also present? If yes, both banks — points toward fuel supply or MAF, not a single-bank vacuum leak.', 'Drivability complaint? Rough idle, hesitation, stall?', 'When does it set — cold start, cruise, or after warm-up?'], 'notes': 'Ford modular V8s and Triton engines: intake manifold gaskets and PCV hoses are extremely common. GM: MAF contamination is the #1 cause. Subaru: cracked intake boots. BMW N54/N55: CCV/PCV system failure.'}, 'P0172': {'code': 'P0172', 'definition': 'System Too Rich (Bank 1)', 'system': 'Fuel/Air Metering', 'severity': 'moderate', 'common_causes': ['Leaking fuel injector', 'Faulty fuel pressure regulator (raw fuel into vacuum line)', 'Failing MAF sensor', 'Failing coolant temp sensor (reading cold all the time)', 'Restricted air filter or air intake', 'Stuck-closed EVAP purge valve flooding intake'], 'diagnostic_steps': ['Verify fuel trims (LTFT < -10% confirms rich)', 'Check fuel pressure regulator vacuum line for fuel presence', 'Inspect air filter and intake for obstructions', 'Scan ECT sensor live data — should match actual engine temp', 'Pull spark plugs, look for black/sooty fouling'], 'follow_up_questions': ['Smell of fuel in oil? Pull dipstick and sniff.', 'Black smoke at tailpipe under throttle?', 'Recent work on injectors, fuel pump, or pressure regulator?'], 'notes': "If oil smells strongly of fuel, suspect a leaking injector or stuck-open injector — don't drive far, fuel dilution kills bearings."}, 'P0174': {'code': 'P0174', 'definition': 'System Too Lean (Bank 2)', 'system': 'Fuel/Air Metering', 'severity': 'moderate', 'common_causes': ['Vacuum leak on bank 2 side of intake', 'Failing MAF sensor (if paired with P0171)', 'Weak fuel pump or restricted filter (if paired with P0171)', 'Exhaust leak before bank 2 O2 sensor'], 'diagnostic_steps': ['Check if P0171 is also set — both banks lean = fuel supply or MAF; single bank = vacuum leak on that side', 'Smoke test the intake, focus on bank 2 side', 'Compare fuel trims bank to bank'], 'follow_up_questions': ['Both P0171 and P0174 present?', 'V-engine, inline, or boxer? (Helps locate bank 2)'], 'notes': "On V-engines, bank 2 is typically the bank opposite cylinder 1. Verify with service info — manufacturers don't all agree on which side is bank 1."}, 'P0300': {'code': 'P0300', 'definition': 'Random/Multiple Cylinder Misfire Detected', 'system': 'Ignition/Fuel', 'severity': 'high', 'common_causes': ['Worn spark plugs across the board (most common, especially overdue maintenance)', 'Vacuum leak causing lean misfire across cylinders', 'Low fuel pressure (weak pump, restricted filter)', 'Failing ignition coil(s) — modern COP setups can have multiple weak coils', 'Bad fuel (water, contamination)', 'Carbon-fouled valves on direct-injection engines', 'EGR valve stuck open'], 'diagnostic_steps': ['Pull all plugs, inspect for wear, fouling, or fuel contamination', 'Check fuel pressure — both static and under load', 'Smoke test intake for vacuum leaks', 'Scan misfire counts per cylinder to look for clustering', 'Inspect EGR valve operation if equipped'], 'follow_up_questions': ['Misfire counts spread evenly or clustered? Even spread points to fuel/vacuum/EGR. Clustering points to one bank or one coil pack.', 'Recent fuel fill-up? Bad fuel is more common than people think.', 'Last plug change interval — has it ever been done?'], 'notes': 'Direct-injection engines (GDI/TDI): valve carbon buildup causes P0300 plus rough cold start. Walnut blasting is the fix. Common on VW/Audi 2.0T, BMW N54/N55, Hyundai Theta II GDI.'}, 'P0301': {'code': 'P0301', 'definition': 'Cylinder 1 Misfire Detected', 'system': 'Ignition/Fuel', 'severity': 'high', 'common_causes': ['Faulty ignition coil (most common on COP setups)', 'Worn or fouled spark plug', 'Clogged or leaking fuel injector', 'Vacuum leak isolated to cylinder 1 (intake gasket)', 'Low compression / mechanical issue (bent valve, broken ring, head gasket)', 'On GM 5.3L AFM/DOD V8s with 100k+: collapsed AFM lifter'], 'diagnostic_steps': ['Pull plug from cylinder 1, inspect condition', 'Swap coil with an adjacent cylinder — see if misfire follows to new cylinder (confirms coil)', "Swap injector with adjacent cylinder if coil swap doesn't move it", 'Compression test if no improvement', 'Listen for AFM lifter tick on GM 5.3 with high miles'], 'follow_up_questions': ['Misfire at idle, under load, or both?', 'Any related codes? P0300, lean codes, cam/crank correlation codes?', 'When did it start — sudden or gradual?', 'Recent work on the vehicle?'], 'notes': "On 5.3L GM AFM/DOD V8s with 100k+ miles, collapsed AFM lifter is the dominant cause when misfire is on cylinder 1, 4, 6, or 7 (the AFM cylinders). Listen for ticking, check for cam lobe damage when you're in there. On Ford modular V8s, COP coil failure is most common — coils typically last 80-120k. Always do the cheap stuff (plug, coil swap) before condemning the long block."}, 'P0302': {'code': 'P0302', 'definition': 'Cylinder 2 Misfire Detected', 'system': 'Ignition/Fuel', 'severity': 'high', 'common_causes': ['Faulty ignition coil', 'Worn or fouled spark plug', 'Clogged or leaking fuel injector', 'Vacuum leak at cylinder 2 intake runner', 'Low compression on cylinder 2'], 'diagnostic_steps': ['Same as P0301 but applied to cylinder 2 — pull plug, swap coil, swap injector, compression check', "Reference vehicle firing order / cylinder layout if cylinder 2 location isn't obvious"], 'follow_up_questions': ['Misfire at idle, under load, or both?', 'Any companion codes?', 'Sudden onset or gradual?'], 'notes': "Same diagnostic flow as any single-cylinder misfire — start cheap, work up to mechanical. Cylinder location varies by engine — don't assume."}, 'P0420': {'code': 'P0420', 'definition': 'Catalyst System Efficiency Below Threshold (Bank 1)', 'system': 'Catalyst/Emissions', 'severity': 'moderate', 'common_causes': ['Failed catalytic converter (genuine catalyst breakdown)', 'Failing rear O2 sensor (mimics low efficiency reading)', 'Exhaust leak between front and rear O2 sensors', 'Unrelated engine issue dumping unburned fuel into cat (misfire, rich condition, oil burning)', "Aftermarket cat that doesn't meet OEM spec"], 'diagnostic_steps': ['FIRST — check for any other engine codes (misfires, lean/rich) that could be killing the cat. Fix those first.', 'Compare front O2 vs rear O2 live data — rear should be slow/steady around 0.7V, not mirroring the front', 'Inspect exhaust for leaks between front and rear O2', 'Tap the cat with a rubber mallet (cold) — rattling = substrate broken loose', 'Temperature test: inlet vs outlet of cat should show ~100°F+ rise when working'], 'follow_up_questions': ['Any other codes set? Cat efficiency codes are often a symptom of upstream problems.', 'Smell of rotten eggs? Often points to a failing cat.', 'Recent misfire history? Catalysts get murdered by repeated misfires.', 'Aftermarket exhaust work done?'], 'notes': "Don't condemn the cat without ruling out the rear O2 sensor first — much cheaper to test. On older Toyotas and Hondas, rear O2 failure is more common than actual cat failure. Federal emissions warranty covers cat to 80k miles / 8 yr on many vehicles — check before customer pays out of pocket."}, 'P0430': {'code': 'P0430', 'definition': 'Catalyst System Efficiency Below Threshold (Bank 2)', 'system': 'Catalyst/Emissions', 'severity': 'moderate', 'common_causes': ['Same as P0420 but bank 2 side', 'Failed catalytic converter on bank 2', 'Failing bank 2 rear O2 sensor', 'Exhaust leak between bank 2 front and rear O2'], 'diagnostic_steps': ['Same diagnostic flow as P0420 but on bank 2 side'], 'follow_up_questions': ['Is P0420 also set? Both cats failing simultaneously is rare unless extreme miles — suspect a different cause.', 'V-engine — bank 2 is opposite cylinder 1 typically.'], 'notes': 'If both P0420 AND P0430 are set, look harder at common causes (bad fuel, oil burning, ECM issue) before blaming both cats at once.'}, 'P0130': {'code': 'P0130', 'definition': 'O2 Sensor Circuit Malfunction (Bank 1 Sensor 1)', 'system': 'Emissions/Sensors', 'severity': 'moderate', 'common_causes': ['Failed upstream O2 sensor', 'Damaged O2 sensor wiring (heat damage, rodent damage)', 'Corroded sensor connector', 'ECM signal/ground issue (rare)'], 'diagnostic_steps': ['Visually inspect sensor and wiring for damage', 'Check sensor voltage signal at idle — should swing between ~0.1V and 0.9V actively', 'Check sensor heater circuit if equipped (often paired with P0135)', 'Wiggle test the connector and harness for intermittent fault'], 'follow_up_questions': ['Intermittent or constant?', 'Recent exhaust work where the sensor was disturbed?'], 'notes': "Heat shielding around O2 sensors matters — if a previous shop left a heat shield off, the sensor cooks early. Aftermarket sensors are usually fine; just don't go bottom-of-the-barrel cheap on these."}, 'P0135': {'code': 'P0135', 'definition': 'O2 Sensor Heater Circuit Malfunction (Bank 1 Sensor 1)', 'system': 'Emissions/Sensors', 'severity': 'low', 'common_causes': ['Open or shorted O2 sensor heater element (sensor failure)', 'Blown heater fuse', 'Wiring damage to heater circuit', 'ECM heater driver failure (rare)'], 'diagnostic_steps': ['Check fuse for O2 sensor heater circuit', 'Measure resistance of heater element (typically 4-15 ohms cold, varies by sensor)', 'Check for 12V at sensor with key on', 'Verify ground side of heater circuit (PCM-controlled)'], 'follow_up_questions': ['Is the engine running rich or rough on cold start? Heater failure delays closed-loop operation.', 'Any other O2 codes?'], 'notes': "Almost always the sensor itself. Replace and move on — don't chase wiring unless you visibly see damage."}, 'P0141': {'code': 'P0141', 'definition': 'O2 Sensor Heater Circuit Malfunction (Bank 1 Sensor 2)', 'system': 'Emissions/Sensors', 'severity': 'low', 'common_causes': ['Failed downstream (post-cat) O2 sensor heater element', 'Wiring damage from heat or rodents', 'Connector corrosion'], 'diagnostic_steps': ['Same as P0135 but for downstream sensor', 'Check heater resistance, fuse, and 12V supply'], 'follow_up_questions': ['Any P0420 also set? Could indicate the sensor is failing both heater and signal.', 'Visible damage to the sensor or pigtail?'], 'notes': "Downstream sensors are exposed to more heat and grime. Replace as a unit (sensor) — don't try to splice the pigtail."}, 'P0440': {'code': 'P0440', 'definition': 'Evaporative Emission Control System Malfunction (General)', 'system': 'EVAP', 'severity': 'low', 'common_causes': ['Loose, damaged, or wrong gas cap (still the #1 cause)', 'Cracked EVAP hose or fitting', 'Failed purge valve / vent valve', 'Charcoal canister cracked or saturated'], 'diagnostic_steps': ['Check gas cap first — proper torque, intact seal, correct part for the vehicle', 'Smoke test the EVAP system', 'Inspect canister and hoses for cracks or damage', 'Activate purge and vent solenoids with scanner, verify operation'], 'follow_up_questions': ['Recent fuel fill-up? Cap may not have been tightened properly.', 'Any fuel smell around the vehicle?', 'When was the gas cap last replaced?'], 'notes': 'ALWAYS check the gas cap first. ALWAYS. People will spend hundreds chasing this and the answer is a $15 cap. Smoke test is the right tool for everything else.'}, 'P0442': {'code': 'P0442', 'definition': 'EVAP System Small Leak Detected', 'system': 'EVAP', 'severity': 'low', 'common_causes': ['Loose or worn gas cap', 'Small crack in EVAP hose or fitting', 'Failing purge or vent valve', 'Cracked charcoal canister'], 'diagnostic_steps': ['Gas cap inspection first', 'Smoke test EVAP system — small leak codes need a fine smoke output to find', 'Pay attention to hose junctions and connector seals'], 'follow_up_questions': ['Any fuel smell?', 'Have you smoke-tested it yet?'], 'notes': "Small leak codes are notoriously frustrating without a smoke machine. If you don't own one yet, this is the code that'll justify the purchase."}, 'P0455': {'code': 'P0455', 'definition': 'EVAP System Large Leak Detected', 'system': 'EVAP', 'severity': 'low', 'common_causes': ['Gas cap missing, loose, or wrong', 'Major EVAP hose disconnected or split', 'Vent valve stuck open', 'Damaged or missing canister'], 'diagnostic_steps': ['Gas cap first — large leak is often a fully missing/loose cap', 'Visually inspect EVAP hoses for disconnection or major damage', 'Smoke test if no obvious cause'], 'follow_up_questions': ['Has anyone been under the vehicle recently — body shop, mechanic, lift hit?', 'Recent fuel pump or fuel filter work?'], 'notes': "Large leaks usually show themselves — a missing hose, a missing cap. Don't overcomplicate it."}, 'P0456': {'code': 'P0456', 'definition': 'EVAP System Very Small Leak Detected', 'system': 'EVAP', 'severity': 'low', 'common_causes': ['Gas cap seal slightly worn', 'Pinhole leak in EVAP hose', 'O-ring or seal at purge/vent valve worn', 'Microcrack in canister'], 'diagnostic_steps': ['Gas cap inspection and seal check', 'Smoke test with low-pressure output to find tiny leaks', 'Inspect O-rings at every threaded EVAP fitting'], 'follow_up_questions': ['Has this code been cleared before and come back?', 'Cold weather only? EVAP plastic shrinks in cold and can leak only when below a certain temp.'], 'notes': "P0456 is the hardest EVAP code. Sometimes you'll chase it for hours and the answer is a $15 cap. Sometimes it's a pinhole in a hose only the smoke machine will find."}, 'P0101': {'code': 'P0101', 'definition': 'Mass Air Flow Sensor Circuit Range/Performance', 'system': 'Fuel/Air Metering', 'severity': 'moderate', 'common_causes': ['Dirty MAF sensor (contaminated with oil, dust)', 'Failing MAF sensor', 'Unmetered air leak (post-MAF vacuum leak)', 'Restricted air filter', 'Aftermarket intake or filter that disrupts airflow'], 'diagnostic_steps': ['Visually inspect MAF for contamination', 'Clean with proper MAF cleaner (NEVER use brake clean or carb cleaner on MAF)', 'Compare MAF readings to expected values at idle (look up spec for engine — usually around 3-7 g/s at idle on V6/V8)', 'Check for vacuum leaks between MAF and throttle body'], 'follow_up_questions': ['Aftermarket intake on the vehicle? Oiled filters contaminate MAF.', "Recent air filter change? Sometimes the air box doesn't seat right.", 'Hesitation under acceleration?'], 'notes': "Oiled K&N-style filters are the #1 MAF killer. If customer has one, clean the MAF, tell them about it, replace MAF if cleaning doesn't work. Use ONLY MAF-specific cleaner."}, 'P0102': {'code': 'P0102', 'definition': 'Mass Air Flow Sensor Circuit Low Input', 'system': 'Fuel/Air Metering', 'severity': 'moderate', 'common_causes': ['Failed MAF sensor (open circuit)', 'MAF connector unplugged or damaged', 'Wiring break in MAF signal circuit', 'Severe MAF contamination'], 'diagnostic_steps': ['Inspect MAF connector — fully seated, no corrosion', 'Check 12V supply and ground at MAF connector', 'Check signal wire continuity to PCM', 'Replace or clean MAF'], 'follow_up_questions': ['Vehicle running rough or stalling?', 'Any work done recently in the engine bay?'], 'notes': "Low input usually means the sensor or its wiring isn't reporting anything. Check the connector before you condemn the sensor."}, 'P0121': {'code': 'P0121', 'definition': 'Throttle Position Sensor Circuit Range/Performance', 'system': 'Fuel/Air Metering', 'severity': 'moderate', 'common_causes': ['Failing TPS (worn wiper inside sensor)', 'Throttle body buildup affecting plate movement', 'Wiring/connector issue', 'On electronic throttle bodies: throttle body failure or carbon buildup'], 'diagnostic_steps': ['Watch TPS live data while slowly opening throttle — look for skips or dropouts', 'Inspect throttle body for carbon buildup affecting smooth operation', 'Check connector and wiring', 'On drive-by-wire systems, perform throttle relearn after cleaning'], 'follow_up_questions': ['Hesitation, surging, or idle issues?', 'Recent throttle body cleaning attempted?'], 'notes': "Modern electronic throttle bodies are sealed units — usually replace, don't repair. Always do a throttle relearn after cleaning or replacement (procedure varies by manufacturer)."}, 'P0325': {'code': 'P0325', 'definition': 'Knock Sensor 1 Circuit Malfunction (Bank 1)', 'system': 'Ignition', 'severity': 'moderate', 'common_causes': ['Failed knock sensor (internal piezoelectric crystal cracked)', 'Damaged knock sensor wiring or connector', 'Loose mounting bolt (must be torqued to spec)', 'On GM LS engines: harness under intake corroded or rodent-damaged'], 'diagnostic_steps': ['Check knock sensor mounting bolt torque', 'Inspect harness — especially on engines where knock sensors live under the intake manifold', 'Resistance test the sensor (typically 90k-100k ohms cold, varies)', 'Inspect for rodent damage if vehicle sits'], 'follow_up_questions': ['Any reduced power / pinging complaints?', 'Vehicle sit for extended periods? Rodents love wiring under intakes.'], 'notes': 'GM LS engines (Vortec 4.8/5.3/6.0) have knock sensors under the intake — replacing them requires intake removal. Plan the labor accordingly. Quote it right.'}, 'P0335': {'code': 'P0335', 'definition': 'Crankshaft Position Sensor Circuit Malfunction', 'system': 'Ignition/Engine Speed', 'severity': 'high', 'common_causes': ['Failed CKP sensor', 'Damaged tone ring on crankshaft', 'Wiring or connector damage', 'Metal debris on sensor tip (magnetic sensors attract iron filings)'], 'diagnostic_steps': ['If no start: check for spark and injector pulse — CKP is critical for both', 'Pull sensor, clean tip of any debris, reinstall and retest', 'Check connector and wiring', 'Scope the signal if available (varies — Hall effect = square wave, magnetic = AC sine wave)'], 'follow_up_questions': ['Intermittent no-start, especially when hot?', 'Stall while driving, then restart after cooling?'], 'notes': "Heat-related CKP failure is classic — vehicle won't restart hot but cranks fine cold, restarts after sitting an hour. Common on older Ford, Nissan, GM. If symptom matches, replace and move on."}, 'P0340': {'code': 'P0340', 'definition': 'Camshaft Position Sensor Circuit Malfunction', 'system': 'Ignition/Timing', 'severity': 'high', 'common_causes': ['Failed CMP sensor', 'Wiring or connector damage', 'Damaged reluctor on camshaft', 'Oil contamination at sensor (worn engine, leaking valve cover gasket)'], 'diagnostic_steps': ['Inspect connector and wiring', 'Pull sensor, inspect tip for oil/debris', 'Scope signal if equipment available', 'Check for related cam timing codes (P0011, P0014, etc.)'], 'follow_up_questions': ['Hard start, especially hot?', 'Stall while driving?', 'Any cam/crank correlation codes (P0016, P0017)?'], 'notes': 'Oil leaking into the CMP connector through the wiring loom (capillary action) is common — fix the leak source too, not just the sensor.'}, 'P0401': {'code': 'P0401', 'definition': 'EGR Insufficient Flow Detected', 'system': 'EGR/Emissions', 'severity': 'low', 'common_causes': ['Carbon-clogged EGR valve', 'Clogged EGR passages in intake', "Failed EGR valve (won't open electrically or vacuum-actuated)", 'Failed DPFE sensor (Ford-specific)', 'Failed EGR pressure feedback sensor'], 'diagnostic_steps': ['Remove EGR valve, inspect and clean carbon buildup', 'Check EGR passages in intake for blockage', 'Verify EGR commanded flow vs actual flow with scanner', 'On Ford: test DPFE sensor'], 'follow_up_questions': ['Mileage? High-mile vehicles have clogged passages.', 'Any pinging under load? (EGR not working can cause pre-ignition)'], 'notes': 'Ford DPFE sensors fail constantly on 4.6/5.4 modular engines. Easy fix, easy money. On most other vehicles, the answer is carbon — clean it before replacing.'}, 'P0117': {'code': 'P0117', 'definition': 'Engine Coolant Temperature Sensor Circuit Low Input', 'system': 'Sensors/Cooling', 'severity': 'moderate', 'common_causes': ['Failed ECT sensor (shorted internally)', 'Wiring short to ground', 'Connector issue'], 'diagnostic_steps': ['Visually inspect ECT and connector', 'Resistance test sensor at known temp vs spec chart', 'Check signal wire for short to ground', 'Replace sensor — usually the answer'], 'follow_up_questions': ['Vehicle running rich? Cold ECT reading makes ECM dump fuel.', 'Gauge reading wrong?'], 'notes': "Most ECT sensors are under $30 — replace before chasing wiring. Always inspect coolant condition while you're in there."}, 'P0128': {'code': 'P0128', 'definition': 'Coolant Thermostat (Coolant Temperature Below Thermostat Regulating Temperature)', 'system': 'Cooling', 'severity': 'low', 'common_causes': ['Stuck-open thermostat (most common — engine warms up slow or never gets to full operating temp)', 'Cold ambient + lots of short trips (rare false trigger)', 'Faulty ECT sensor reading low'], 'diagnostic_steps': ['Verify coolant temp gauge — does it ever reach normal operating range?', 'Compare ECT live data to expected after 15+ min runtime — should be 195-220°F typically', 'Replace thermostat if stuck open'], 'follow_up_questions': ['Heater output weak? Classic stuck-open thermostat symptom.', 'Mileage on the coolant / when was the t-stat last replaced?'], 'notes': "If they're complaining about weak heat in winter, P0128 is usually the smoking gun. Easy fix, customer feels the improvement immediately."}, 'P0500': {'code': 'P0500', 'definition': 'Vehicle Speed Sensor Malfunction', 'system': 'Drivetrain/Sensors', 'severity': 'moderate', 'common_causes': ['Failed VSS', 'Wiring/connector damage', 'Damaged tone ring', 'On vehicles using ABS for speed: bad ABS wheel speed sensor or module issue'], 'diagnostic_steps': ['Inspect VSS and connector (often on transmission)', "Check speedometer operation — works or doesn't?", 'On vehicles using ABS for VSS: scan ABS module for codes too', 'Resistance/voltage test sensor'], 'follow_up_questions': ['Speedometer working?', 'Cruise control inoperative?', 'ABS or traction control light on?'], 'notes': 'Modern vehicles often use ABS wheel speed sensors as the vehicle speed input — a single bad wheel speed sensor can set P0500 plus ABS codes. Diagnose ABS first on those.'}, 'P0506': {'code': 'P0506', 'definition': 'Idle Air Control System RPM Lower Than Expected', 'system': 'Idle/Air Metering', 'severity': 'low', 'common_causes': ['Carbon buildup at throttle plate / IAC passage', 'Failed IAC valve (older vehicles with mechanical IAC)', "Vacuum leak (counterintuitive — but ECM can't compensate fast enough)", 'Dirty throttle body needing cleaning + relearn'], 'diagnostic_steps': ['Clean throttle body (electronic throttle systems need relearn after)', 'Inspect IAC valve on older vehicles', 'Smoke test for vacuum leaks', 'Perform idle relearn procedure per manufacturer'], 'follow_up_questions': ['Idle stalls or just runs low?', 'Recent throttle body work without a relearn?'], 'notes': 'On drive-by-wire systems, ALWAYS do the idle relearn procedure after cleaning the throttle body. Skipping it sets P0506 or P0507. Procedure varies — look it up per vehicle.'}, 'P0507': {'code': 'P0507', 'definition': 'Idle Air Control System RPM Higher Than Expected', 'system': 'Idle/Air Metering', 'severity': 'low', 'common_causes': ['Vacuum leak (most common — ECM trying to lean back, idle stays high)', 'Throttle plate stuck partially open (carbon)', 'Failed IAC valve stuck open', 'Sticking throttle pedal/cable (older mechanical)', 'Aftermarket intake leak'], 'diagnostic_steps': ['Smoke test the intake for vacuum leaks FIRST', 'Clean throttle body and perform idle relearn', 'Inspect IAC on older vehicles', 'Check for cracked vacuum lines, especially brake booster line'], 'follow_up_questions': ['Idle stays high after warm-up, or just at startup?', 'Recent intake work or aftermarket parts?'], 'notes': 'P0507 = vacuum leak until proven otherwise. Smoke test, find the leak, fix it. The IAC and throttle body are downstream of the actual problem 80% of the time.'}, 'P0014': {'code': 'P0014', 'definition': 'Camshaft Position Actuator B - Timing Over-Advanced or System Performance (Bank 1)', 'system': 'Variable Valve Timing', 'severity': 'high', 'common_causes': ['Stuck VVT solenoid (clogged with oil sludge)', 'Failed VVT phaser', 'Low oil pressure (worn pump, sludged engine)', 'Failed CMP sensor', 'Wrong oil viscosity for the engine', 'Overdue oil change causing varnish in VVT system'], 'diagnostic_steps': ['Check oil level AND condition first — VVT codes are very oil-sensitive', 'Remove VVT solenoid, inspect for sludge, clean and reinstall', 'If still set, oil pressure test', 'Check for related codes (P0011, P0017, P0341)'], 'follow_up_questions': ['When was the last oil change? With what oil?', 'Cold-start rattle for a few seconds?', 'GM 5.3 AFM/DOD engine? (Common pattern.)'], 'notes': 'GM 5.3L AFM engines are notorious for this. Oil-related VVT failures are huge — many cases resolve with a thorough oil flush and fresh full-synthetic of correct viscosity. If the phaser is mechanically damaged, replacement is required and labor-heavy. Always tie this back to oil maintenance history.'}, 'P0496': {'code': 'P0496', 'definition': 'EVAP System Flow During Non-Purge Condition (GM-specific common)', 'system': 'EVAP', 'severity': 'low', 'common_causes': ['Stuck-open EVAP purge valve', 'Damaged purge valve solenoid', 'Vacuum leak in EVAP system between purge valve and intake'], 'diagnostic_steps': ['Test purge valve operation with scanner', 'Inspect purge valve and lines', 'Replace purge valve — usually the answer on GM'], 'follow_up_questions': ['Stall after fill-up or at idle?', 'GM vehicle? (P0496 is heavily GM-flavored.)'], 'notes': 'On GM trucks and crossovers (Silverado, Equinox, Traverse, etc.) P0496 = bad purge solenoid 90% of the time. Cheap part, easy replacement, customer happy.'}, 'U0100': {'code': 'U0100', 'definition': 'Lost Communication with ECM/PCM', 'system': 'Network/Communication', 'severity': 'high', 'common_causes': ['Damaged CAN bus wiring (chafe, rodent damage)', 'Failed ECM/PCM', 'Loss of power or ground to ECM', 'Other module on bus pulling network down', 'Corroded body/chassis grounds'], 'diagnostic_steps': ['Verify power and ground at ECM connector', 'Check chassis grounds — common failure point', "Scan all modules — see which ones communicate and which don't", 'Inspect CAN bus wiring for damage', 'Disconnect modules one at a time to isolate which is pulling bus down (last resort)'], 'follow_up_questions': ['Multiple modules dropping off network or just ECM?', 'Vehicle sit in a barn / rodent territory?', 'Recent water intrusion (flood, leaks)?'], 'notes': 'U-codes are network codes — start with grounds and power, then move to wiring. ECM replacement should be a last resort, not a first guess. Programming and security on a new module is expensive and time-consuming.'}}
